\description{
Creates the rate matrix that describes how your discrete character evolves.
Before fitting any model in RateScape, you need to specify the rules of
character evolution — which state transitions are possible and whether they
happen at the same or different rates. This function builds that matrix.

\strong{Which model should I use?}
\itemize{
  \item \strong{Mk} (\code{model = "mk"}): The simplest option. All transitions
    between states happen at the same rate. Good default for binary traits or
    when you have no reason to expect asymmetric evolution. Start here if
    unsure.
  \item \strong{SYM} (\code{model = "sym"}): Forward and reverse transitions
    between any pair of states have the same rate, but different pairs can
    differ. For example, transitions between states 0 and 1 might be common,
    while transitions between 0 and 2 are rare. Useful for multi-state
    characters where you expect some transitions to be easier than others.
  \item \strong{ARD} (\code{model = "ard"}): Every transition gets its own
    rate. The transition from state 0 to 1 can differ from 1 to 0. This is
    the most flexible model but requires more data. Use for traits where
    gains and losses clearly differ in frequency (e.g., gaining a complex
    structure is harder than losing it).
  \item \strong{Chromosome} (\code{model = "chromosome"}): Specialized for
    chromosome number evolution. Allows gains (+1), losses (-1), and
    optionally polyploidy (doubling) events. See the chromePlus package
    for extended chromosome models.
  \item \strong{Custom} (\code{model = "custom"}): Supply your own Q matrix
    for non-standard models.
}
